---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { artists } from '../../data/artists';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Nordweg"
  description="Who is behind Nordweg: musicians from Nordwald Records (Domsgard, Eldruna) who set Norse history to music and tell it here, grounded in the original sources."
  lang="en"
  altUrl="/ueber-uns"
>
  <section class="container about">
    <header class="about-hero reveal">
      <p class="eyebrow">Who keeps this chronicle</p>
      <h1>About Nordweg</h1>
      <p class="about-lede text-dim">
        Nordweg is a chronicle of the Viking world: gods and sagas, runes and ships, daily life
        and doom. Written by people who do not just study that world - they give it music.
      </p>
    </header>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <div class="about-body reveal">
      <h2>Why Nordweg exists</h2>
      <p>
        Nordweg is a project by musicians. Behind this blog stands the independent label
        <a href="https://nordwaldrecords.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Nordwald Records</a>
        with its two artists, Domsgard and Eldruna. If you write songs about Odin, Ragnarok or
        the voyages of the longships, you inevitably spend long nights among Eddas, sagas and
        excavation reports. Out of that research grew more than lyrics: the wish to tell the
        stories behind the music properly, with care and depth.
      </p>
      <p>
        To us, history and music belong together. The old sources give our songs their depth,
        and the music gives the old stories a voice people want to hear again today. Nordweg is
        where the two meet.
      </p>

      <h2>How we work</h2>
      <p>
        Every article on Nordweg is written along the original sources: the Poetic Edda, the
        Prose Edda of Snorri Sturluson, the Icelandic sagas, and the archaeological finds from
        Scandinavia and the old trade routes of the North. Where scholars disagree or the
        evidence runs thin, we say so openly instead of filling the gaps with fantasy.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every article lists its sources at the end - so you can read on and check for yourself.
        Photos of historical finds come from free archives such as Wikimedia Commons and are
        always shown with credit.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <div class="about-music reveal">
      <h2>The music behind it</h2>
      <p>
        If reading these pages leaves you longing for the North: there is a soundtrack for
        that.
      </p>

      <div class="artist-cards">
        <article class="artist-card">
          <p class="eyebrow">Epic. Battle.</p>
          <h3>Domsgard</h3>
          <p class="text-dim">
            Drums, choirs and the thunder of battle. Music for shield walls, kings' sagas and
            the long march north.
          </p>
          <div class="card-links">
            <a class="btn" href={artists.domsgard.spotifyUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Spotify</a>
            <a class="btn" href={artists.domsgard.youtubeUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">YouTube</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="artist-card">
          <p class="eyebrow">Atmospheric. Folk.</p>
          <h3>Eldruna</h3>
          <p class="text-dim">
            Mist over the fjord, runes by the fire, quiet voices from an older age. Atmospheric
            Viking music to sink into.
          </p>
          <div class="card-links">
            <a class="btn" href={artists.eldruna.spotifyUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Spotify</a>
            <a class="btn" href={artists.eldruna.youtubeUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">YouTube</a>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>

      <p>
        Both projects are released through
        <a href="https://nordwaldrecords.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Nordwald Records</a>,
        our small label for Nordic music.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <div class="about-contact reveal">
      <h2>Contact</h2>
      <p>
        Questions, suggestions or a correction to an article? You can reach us through the
        channels of our label,
        <a href="https://nordwaldrecords.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Nordwald Records</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about {
    max-width: var(--maxw-prose);
    padding-top: 3.5rem;
    padding-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  .about-hero { text-align: center; }
  .about-hero h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 6vw, 3.2rem);
    margin: 0.7rem 0 1rem;
  }
  .about-lede {
    max-width: 56ch;
    margin: 0 auto;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
  }
  .about h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-title);
    font-size: 1.45rem;
    margin: 2.4rem 0 0.7rem;
    color: var(--color-bronze-bright);
  }
  .about h2:first-child { margin-top: 0; }
  .about p { line-height: 1.8; }

  /* ---------- Artist mini cards ---------- */
  .artist-cards {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
  }
  .artist-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1.5rem 1.4rem;
    background: linear-gradient(150deg, rgba(201, 162, 90, 0.06), var(--color-bg-raised));
    transition: border-color 0.25s ease, transform 0.25s ease;
  }
  .artist-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-bronze-dim);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }
  .artist-card h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    margin: 0.4rem 0 0.5rem;
    color: var(--color-parchment);
  }
  .artist-card p { margin: 0 0 1.1rem; font-size: 0.98rem; line-height: 1.65; }
  .artist-card .eyebrow { margin: 0; font-size: 0.68rem; }
  .card-links { display: flex; gap: 0.6rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .card-links .btn { padding: 0.5rem 1.1rem; font-size: 0.9rem; }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .artist-cards { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .artist-card { padding: 1.3rem 1.15rem; }
  }
</style>
